 begins in 1400 BC, making it the oldest European capital city\n|-\n|-\n| [[Chania]]\n| [[Crete]]\n| {{Hs|Gre}}[[Crete]], Greece\n| data-sort-value=\"-1700\" | c. 1700\u20131500 BC<ref name=\"Hogan\">{{cite web |url=http://www.themodernantiquarian.com/site/10881/cydonia.html#fieldnotes |title=Cydonia |publisher=The Modern Antiquarian |date=January 23, 2008 |accessdate=March 31, 2012 |author=Hogan, C Michael |quote=The most powerful centre of western Crete, Cydonia produced Bronze Age pottery and Linear B writings circa 1700 to 1500 BC, and was one of the first cities of Europe to mint coinage. (Pashley, 1837)}}</ref>{{Unreliable source?|date=September 2016}}<!-- see talk -->\n| [[Minoan civilisation|Minoan]] foundation as [[Kydonia]].\n|-\n| [[Thebes, Greece|Thebes]]\n| Mycenaean Greece\n| {{Hs|Gre}}[[Boeotia]], Greece\n| data-sort-value=\"-1600\" | c. 1600\u20131250 BC<ref name=\"Wilson2006\">{{cite book|author=Nigel Guy Wilson|title=Encyclopedia of Ancient Greece|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-aFtPdh6-2QC&pg=PA695|year=2006|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=978-0-415-97334-2|pages=695\u2013}}</ref>\n| [[Mycenaean Greece|Mycenaean]] foundation.\n|-\n| [[Larnaca]]\n| [[Alashiya]]\n| [[Cyprus]]\n| data-sort-value=\"-1400\" | c. 1400 BC{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n| [[Mycenaean Greece|Mycenaean]], then [[Phoenicia]]n colony.\n|-\n| [[Trikala]]\n| Mycenaean Greece\n| {{Hs|Gre}}[[Thessaly]], Greece\n| data-sort-value=\"-1200.1\" | before 1200 BC{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n| Founded as ''Trikke''.\n|-\n| [[Chalcis]]\n| Mycenaean Greece\n| Greece\n| data-sort-value=\"-1200.1\" | before 1200 BC{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n| Mentioned by [[Homer]].\n|-\n| [[Lisbon]]\n| Ulissipo (Phoenician)\n| [[Portugal]]\n| data-sort-value=\"1\" | c.1200 BC<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.worldatlas.com/articles/the-oldest-cities-in-europe.html|title=The Oldest Cities in Europe|website=WorldAtlas}}</ref>\n| Second-oldest European capital city\n|-\n| [[C\u00e1diz]]\n| [[Carthaginian Iberia]]\n| {{Hs|Spa}} [[Andalusia]], Spain\n| data-sort-value=\"-1104\" | 1104 BC\n| Founded around 1104 BC as Gadir or Agadir by [[Phoenicians]] from Tyre.\n|-\n| [[Patras]]\n| [[Mycenaean Greece]]\n| Greece\n| data-sort-value=\"-1100\" | c. 1100 BC{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n| Founded by [[Patreus]].\n|-\n| [[Chios (town)|Chios]] \n| [[Chios]] \n| {{Hs|Gre}}[[North Aegean]], Greece \n| data-sort-value=\"-1100\" | c. 1100 BC{{citation needed|date=June 2016}} \n|\n|-\n| [[Nicosia]]\n| [[Mycenaean Greece]]\n| [[Cyprus]]\n| data-sort-value=\"-1050\" | c. 1050 BC{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n| [[Mycenaean Greece|Mycenaean]] foundation as [[Ledra]]. Archaeological evidence of continuous habitation since the beginning of the [[Bronze Age]] 2500 years BC.{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n|-\n| [[Zadar]] \n| [[Illyria|Illyricum]]\n| [[Croatia]]\n| data-sort-value=\"-1000\" | c. 1000 BC{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n| Founded by [[Liburnians]]. Oldest continuously inhabited city in [[Croatia]]. Main Liburnian settlement.\n|-\n| [[Mtskheta]] \n| [[Caucasian Iberia]] \n| [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]\n| data-sort-value=\"-1000\" | c. 1000 BC{{citation needed|date=June 2016}} \n| Remains of towns at this location have been dated to earlier than the year 1000 BC, and Mtskheta was capital of the early Georgian Kingdom of [[Caucasian Iberia|Iberia]] during the 3rd century BC \u2013 5th century AD. It was the site of early [[Christianity|Christian]] activity, and the location where Christianity was proclaimed the [[state religion]] of Georgia in 337.\n|-\n| [[Mytilene]] \n| [[Lesbos Island|Lesbos]] \n| {{Hs|Gre}}[[North Aegean]], Greece \n| data-sort-value=\"-1000\" | 10th century BC{{citation needed|date=June 2016}} \n|\n|-\n| [[Vani]] \n| [[Colchis]] \n| {{Hs|Geo}} [[Imereti]], [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] \n| data-sort-value=\"-800.1\" | before 8th century BC<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.great-adventures.com/destinations/rep_georgia/colchis.html|title=COLCHIS, THE LAND OF THE GOLDEN FLEECE, REPUBLIC OF GEORGIA|website=www.great-adventures.com|access-date=2017-03-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://eurasia.travel/georgia/places/western_georgia/kutaisi/vani/|title=Vani|website=eurasia.travel}}</ref>\n|\n|-\n| [[Seville]]\n| [[Prehistoric Iberia#Iron Age|Iron Age Iberia]]\n| {{Hs|Spa}} [[Andalusia]], Spain\n| data-sort-value=\"-800\" | 8th century BC{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n|founded as [[Tartessos|Tartessian]] ''Spal''.<ref>{{cite book|author=Manuel Jes\u00fas Rold\u00e1n Salgueiro|title=Historia de Sevilla|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zZXEGgAACAAJ|accessdate=9 February 2013|year=2007|publisher=Almuzara|isbn=978-84-88586-24-7}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[M\u00e1laga]]\n| [[Prehistoric Iberia#Iron Age|Iron Age Iberia]]\n| {{Hs|Spa}} [[Andalusia]], Spain\n| data-sort-value=\"-800\" | 8th century BC{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n|founded as [[Phoenicia]]n ''Malaka''.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=B7SLWT2vpNcC&lpg=PA310&dq=Phoenician%20Malaka&pg=PA305#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Phoenicians and the West|publisher=|accessdate=15 October 2015|isbn=9780521795432|last1=Semmler|first1=Mar\u00eda Eugenia Aubet|last2=Aubet|first2=Maria Eugenia|date=2001-09-06}}</ref>{{page needed|date=June 2016}}\n|-\n| [[Mdina]]\n| [[History of Malta#Antiquity|Antiquity Malta]]\n| {{Hs|Mlt}} [[Malta]]\n| data-sort-value=\"-800\" | 8th century BC<ref>Cassar, Carmel (2000). A Concise History of Malta. Msida: Mireva Publications. {{ISBN|1870579526}}</ref>\n|founded as [[Phoenicia]]n ''[[Melite (ancient city)|Melite]]''.\n|-\n| [[Cagliari]] \n| [[Sardinia]] \n| {{Hs|Ita}}[[Sardinia]], Italy \n| data-sort-value=\"-800\" | 8th century BC{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n|Founded by [[Phoenicia]]ns from [[Tyre, Lebanon|Tyre]] as Krly, Caralis in Roman times, Callaris in Middle Ages.\n|-\n| [[Messina]] (as Zancle) \n| [[History of Sicily|Sicily]] \n| {{Hs|Ita}}[[Sicily]], Italy \n| data-sort-val