OGY''. Edited by David Braiind (Prof, of University of Exeter (UK)) // Olar LORDKIPANIDZE CENTRE OF ARCHAEOLOGY OF GEORGIAN NATIONAL MUSEUM. P. 43 \"According to the data on archaeological excavations on the Gabashvili, Dateshidze and Ukimerioni hills in Kutaisi, an urban-type settlement of the 6-5 cent. BC was found to be concentrated\"</ref>\n|-\n| [[Varna]] \n| [[Thrace]] \n| {{Hs|Bul}}[[Bulgarian Black Sea Coast]], [[Bulgaria]] \n| data-sort-value=\"-585\" | 585\u2013570 BC{{citation needed|date=June 2016}} \n| Founded<ref>An Inventory of Archaic and Classical Poleis: An Investigation Conducted by The Copenhagen Polis Centre for the Danish National Research Foundation by Mogens Herman Hansen, 2005, page 936,</ref> as [[Varna|Odessos]] by settlers from the Greek city of [[Miletus]].\n|-\n| [[Sant Mart\u00ed d'Emp\u00faries]] (as Emporion) \n| [[Iberia]] \n| [[Catalonia]], Spain \n| data-sort-value=\"-575\" | c. 575 BC{{citation needed|date=June 2016}} \n| A colony of the Greek city of [[Phocaea]]. Present Sant Mart\u00ed is on the ancient Palaiopolis of Emporion, in an island next to the coast; in 550 BC, the inhabitants moved to the mainland, creating the Neapolis: Palaiapolis remained as a small neighbourhood.\n|-\n| [[Lamia (city)|Lamia]]\n|\n| Greece\n| data-sort-value=\"-500\" | before the 5th century BC{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n| Greek city. First mentioned 424 BC\n|-\n| [[Serres]] \n| [[Macedonia (ancient kingdom)|Macedonia]]\n| Greece \n| data-sort-value=\"-500\" | 5th century BC{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n| Greek city. First mentioned in the 5th century BC as ''Siris''.\n|-\n| [[Veria]] \n| [[Macedonia (ancient kingdom)|Macedonia]]|| Greece \n| data-sort-value=\"-432\" | c. 432 BC{{citation needed|date=June 2016}} \n| Greek city. First mentioned by [[Thucydides]] in 432 BC.\n|-\n| [[Rhodes (city)|Rhodes]] \n| [[Rhodes]], [[Aegean Sea]] \n| {{Hs|Gre}}[[Dodecanese]], Greece \n| data-sort-value=\"-408\" |  c. 408 BC{{citation needed|date=June 2016}} \n| Greek city.\n|-\n| [[Plovdiv]]\n| [[Thrace]]\n|{{Hs|Bul}}[[Plovdiv Province]], [[Bulgaria]]\n|   \n|  Site inhabited since Neolithic times. Hypothesized that it was precisely in the 4th Century BC when Philipopolis (Plovdiv) emerged as a city.\n|-\n|[[Bitola]] (as [[Heraclea Lyncestis]])\n|[[Macedonia (ancient kingdom)]]\n|[[North Macedonia]]\n|4th century BC\n|Founded by [[Philip II of Macedon]], the father of [[Alexander the Great]]\n|-\n| [[Sofia]] \n| [[Moesia]] \n| {{Hs|Bul}}[[Sofia Valley]], [[Bulgaria]] \n| data-sort-value=\"-400\" | 4th century BC{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n| [[Celts|Celtic]] foundation as ''[[Serdika|Serdica]]''.<ref>The Cambridge Ancient History, Volume 3, Part 2: The Assyrian and Babylonian Empires and Other States of the Near East, from the Eighth to the Sixth Centuries BC by John Boardman, I. E. S. Edwards, E. Sollberger, and N. G. L. Hammond, {{ISBN|0-521-22717-8}}, 1992, page 600: \"In the place of the vanished Treres and Tilataei we find the Serdi for whom there is no evidence before the first century BC. It has for long being supposed on convincing linguistic and archeological grounds that this tribe was of Celtic origin.\"</ref>\n|-\n| [[Metz]] \n| [[Gaul]] \n| France \n| data-sort-value=\"-400\" | 4th century BC{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n| Founded as the [[oppidum]] of [[celts|Celtic]] [[Mediomatrici]]. However, human permanent presence has been established in the site since 2500 BC.\n|-\n| [[Roses, Girona|Roses]] (as Rhode) \n| [[Iberia]] \n| {{Hs|Spa}}[[Catalonia]], Spain \n| data-sort-value=\"-400\" | 4th century BC{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}\n| The exactly origin of the city is unknown, but there are remains of a [[Ancient Greece|Greek]] colony from the 4th century BC, although some historians consider the foundation earlier, at the 8th century BC. However, permanent human presence has been established in the site since 3000 BC as evidenced by the different [[megalithic]] monuments surrou